The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Srinagar, Aug. 5: Eight militants have been killed in separate clashes along Kashmirs LoC since yesterday.           
	The surge in violence comes at a time security forces have been preoccupied with containing street protests. A top Hizb-ul-Mujahideen commander, said to be active since 1995, was also shot down in a separate encounter in Jammus Doda today.           
	The spurt in violence followed reports that militants were regrouping to launch attacks on the security forces. The army listed four infiltration bids during the past 24 hours.           
	The first encounter occurred at Tangdhar in north Kashmir last evening where three militants were shot down. The gun battle with the other militants in the group was on till this evening.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Delhi police on Wednesday said it had no records of licences of three firearms recovered from the residence of Buta Singhs son Sarobjit, arrested by the CBI in connection with a bribery case.                  
	 Delhi: U.K.Bansal on Wednesday took over as special secretary (internal security) in the ministry of home affairs. Bansal, a 1974 batch UP cadre IPS officer, was special director-general in the BSF before the appointments committee of the cabinet cleared his name for the post on Tuesday. He replaces Raman Srivastava who took over as BSF director-general.                  
	 Amarnath (PTI): The two-month-long Amarnath yatra concluded on Wednesday amid heightened threats from militants and bad weather. Nearly four lakh pilgrims were assisted by dog squads and armed forces who provided multi-layered security during their trek to the cave shrine.                  
	 Washington (PTI): Thousands of Indian Americans are expected to participate in the India Day Parade in Edison, New Jersey, this weekend, organisers said on Wednesday. Television presenter Mandira Bedi will lead the mile-long parade.                                                                                                                            
